WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:36.100 --> 00:00:43.940
﻿Tell me, after Ivano left,
who were your players?

00:00:45.660 --> 00:00:47.540
Is it Hansen?

00:00:47.780 --> 00:00:52.620
Which other handball players
did you particularly respect

00:00:52.900 --> 00:00:58.020
and wish to compete with individually?

00:00:58.300 --> 00:01:03.420
For example, it was Dule Duvnjak,
who played at the same time as Ivano,

00:01:03.700 --> 00:01:06.811
and later succeeded him
in that position.

00:01:07.042 --> 00:01:10.795
Later, it was Mikkel Hansen
from the Danish national team.

00:01:10.965 --> 00:01:17.702
I had a lot of duels against him.
And later we played together at PSG.

00:01:18.060 --> 00:01:23.460
So, that rivalry between us
eventually settled down.

00:01:24.660 --> 00:01:29.620
Because I have no ties to Denmark,
but I do have ties with Croatia.

00:01:29.940 --> 00:01:35.620
My father was born there,
and my roots are from Croatia.

00:01:35.860 --> 00:01:39.140
So, I've never experienced
that same feeling of rivalry

00:01:39.340 --> 00:01:41.820
when playing against Croatia
and Ivano,

00:01:42.100 --> 00:01:45.980
like I do when playing against
any other national team.

00:01:46.220 --> 00:01:49.940
Of course, we fought against
M. Hansen and Denmark for a long time.

00:01:50.180 --> 00:01:54.300
Now, they have caught up with us
and taken over that dominance.

00:01:54.540 --> 00:01:58.220
Unfortunately, but that's the truth.
That's how it is in the world of sports.

00:01:58.500 --> 00:02:03.140
It's true that we fought for a long time
against Mikkel to see who was better.

00:02:03.420 --> 00:02:06.460
At the same time, we played together,
so we became friends.

00:02:06.660 --> 00:02:09.740
And that rivalry is no longer as strong.

00:02:10.020 --> 00:02:13.500
Was there ever a rivalry
between you and Luka?

00:02:13.740 --> 00:02:19.620
And did you ever want to prove to him
what he had to do to reach your level?

00:02:20.780 --> 00:02:28.460
Yes, I treated Luka like an older brother.
His story is incredible.

00:02:28.700 --> 00:02:30.460
He played tennis really well.

00:02:30.700 --> 00:02:35.860
Yes, we constantly played tennis
with our father and mother.

00:02:36.180 --> 00:02:40.020
More for fun, and he was
really good at it.

00:02:40.260 --> 00:02:44.100
At the age of ten, he decided
he only wanted to pursue tennis.

00:02:44.260 --> 00:02:47.260
And when he was 20, he was
supposed to go to San Rafael,

00:02:47.620 --> 00:02:51.020
so he could study and play tennis there.

00:02:51.740 --> 00:02:55.340
Between the ages of 13 and 14, he was
number one player in France. -Yes.

00:02:55.620 --> 00:03:01.180
I dreamed of traveling to Roland Garros
and Wimbledon and watching him play there.

00:03:01.460 --> 00:03:05.620
We watched tennis matches,
watched Ivanišević winning Wimbledon.

00:03:05.820 --> 00:03:08.620
We were his big fans.
Luka played tennis all day long.

00:03:08.711 --> 00:03:11.419
Then, at the age of 19,
he decided to start playing handball.

00:03:11.496 --> 00:03:13.904
That's when we started dreaming
about one day playing together.

00:03:14.050 --> 00:03:16.130
It was an incredible time.

00:03:16.285 --> 00:03:19.925
There was never any rivalry
between the two of us.

00:03:20.352 --> 00:03:26.412
For example, if he won a tennis match,
I felt like it was my victory too.

00:03:26.946 --> 00:03:33.666
When we started playing together,
I felt a lot of pressure because I wanted...

00:03:34.140 --> 00:03:40.087
When he decided to return to handball at 19,
I was 23 or 24 at the time

00:03:40.192 --> 00:03:43.337
and already the best player in the world.
I had already won an Olympic medal,

00:03:43.421 --> 00:03:45.381
a World and a European Championship.

00:03:45.597 --> 00:03:49.437
And suddenly, I had the opportunity
to play with Luka.

00:03:49.685 --> 00:03:53.205
To teach him how to play,
to pass on all the knowledge

00:03:53.278 --> 00:03:56.398
I had learned from Noka and from playing
with the French national team.

00:03:56.507 --> 00:03:57.962
I had to help him.

00:03:58.120 --> 00:04:01.880
It was an honor to play with my brother,
but at the same time, I felt pressure.

00:04:02.980 --> 00:04:06.220
My goal was for us to succeed together.

00:04:06.460 --> 00:04:13.502
That period was very emotional for me,
but I also felt a bit of pressure.

00:04:13.806 --> 00:04:20.338
Because you didn't play alone.
I felt a kind of responsibility toward him.

00:04:22.460 --> 00:04:27.987
Now, when you look back on your career
and speak clearly and simply...

00:04:28.500 --> 00:04:33.300
What was it that made you well known?
Where did you feel you dominated?

00:04:34.300 --> 00:04:38.700
Let's leave aside your mother's words
that you always knew what you wanted.

00:04:39.020 --> 00:04:43.700
Where did that confidence
and responsibility come from,

00:04:43.940 --> 00:04:47.659
to score the most goals in
the most important matches?

00:04:48.020 --> 00:04:52.540
Was it your shooting,
or maybe your versatility?

00:04:53.718 --> 00:04:59.333
What did you have that was better
than all the other players?

00:05:02.444 --> 00:05:16.335
In my opinion, it was something inside me,
an "energy" that I had to be the best.

00:05:19.295 --> 00:05:25.365
Of course, I was physically,
technically, and mentally strong,

00:05:25.541 --> 00:05:27.661
but I had something internal.

00:05:27.826 --> 00:05:32.458
I don't know where it came from -
maybe I inherited it from my father

00:05:32.623 --> 00:05:36.747
or from my ancestors. That
was my greatest strength.

00:05:37.540 --> 00:05:39.416
What you said is true.

00:05:39.627 --> 00:05:43.838
I don't know why, but I always
played my best in finals. -That's true.

00:05:44.660 --> 00:05:48.700
Now that my career is over,
and I watch some of those matches,

00:05:48.940 --> 00:05:53.180
which I never used to do because
I always wanted to move forward,

00:05:53.460 --> 00:05:58.500
I think to myself: how did I even
manage to score those goals?

00:05:59.620 --> 00:06:03.300
In the first final against Pamplona,
in the Champions League with Montpellier,

00:06:03.540 --> 00:06:06.580
I shot a "dry leaf" with my left hand.

00:06:06.742 --> 00:06:11.201
When I watch some of those goals, it feels
like there was some higher force at play.

00:06:11.302 --> 00:06:13.951
Like you were in a trance.
-Yes, there's a higher force.

00:06:14.142 --> 00:06:19.130
My father always told me
that in the most difficult moments,

00:06:19.258 --> 00:06:21.629
you see who the best players are.

00:06:21.830 --> 00:06:25.810
When it's toughest. -Yes, in finals,
you see who the great players are.

00:06:26.264 --> 00:06:31.834
Maybe I inherited that from my father,
but that was my biggest strength.

00:06:32.499 --> 00:06:37.841
I had something in me
that helped me be the best.

00:06:38.610 --> 00:06:43.146
The goal I would set for myself
was my biggest strength.

00:06:43.660 --> 00:06:48.620
But you still had to have talent,
because there are many players

00:06:48.900 --> 00:06:51.060
with a huge desire to win
but without talent.

00:06:51.340 --> 00:06:53.820
Although, let's say...

00:06:54.380 --> 00:06:58.900
There are players like Messi and
Ronaldo, or Federer and Đoković.

00:07:01.660 --> 00:07:04.590
Newspapers wrote that Balić
was the new Mozart of handball.

00:07:04.727 --> 00:07:09.082
So who would you compare yourself to?
Terminator, Rammstein, Wagner...

00:07:09.674 --> 00:07:11.674
You had tremendous strength.

00:07:12.007 --> 00:07:17.607
When you watch Ivano play,
it all looks easy, almost like

00:07:21.900 --> 00:07:24.940
he's playing basketball.

00:07:25.303 --> 00:07:30.414
For most of the goals he scored,
you can't even explain how he did it.

00:07:30.660 --> 00:07:34.980
Like when you watch Federer,
tennis seems easy.

00:07:35.180 --> 00:07:42.220
Or when you watch Messi. I was
maybe more like Đoković or Ronaldo.

00:07:44.460 --> 00:07:48.009
Because I trained a lot,
I had discipline,

00:07:49.820 --> 00:07:54.700
daily motivation to learn something new
and to become better.

00:07:55.020 --> 00:08:00.900
I trained to reach my limit and maybe
even beyond what my physical

00:08:01.140 --> 00:08:06.500
and mental capabilities allowed.
In that sense, I think

00:08:06.740 --> 00:08:12.300
I'm more like Đoković.
We know he gives his all every day,

00:08:12.540 --> 00:08:16.980
he's disciplined, and that
helps him to be the best.

00:08:17.260 --> 00:08:22.500
And not just to be the best
but to constantly push

00:08:22.820 --> 00:08:25.940
both physical and mental limits.

00:08:26.140 --> 00:08:29.340
When you watch his matches,
you can sense there's something more.

00:08:29.540 --> 00:08:37.540
Of course, he's technically,
tactically, and mentally very strong.

00:08:37.820 --> 00:08:41.843
But there's something else-something
that can't easily be explained.

00:08:41.958 --> 00:08:45.241
And that's something inside him.
-Exactly. He's a player that everyone

00:08:45.364 --> 00:08:48.632
loves right away.
Maybe you weren't like that,

00:08:48.849 --> 00:08:53.452
but you were a "monster"
and a guarantee for gold medal.

00:08:54.660 --> 00:08:58.134
You know who I ran into recently,
and he said something really great

00:08:58.246 --> 00:09:01.446
just a few days ago, when I was in Split.
I was having a coffee, and Drago Vuković

00:09:01.608 --> 00:09:04.009
happened to walk by.
He sends his regards.

00:09:04.168 --> 00:09:06.559
Drago was a great player
and a really good person.

00:09:08.295 --> 00:09:13.327
I invited him over and told him
I was going to meet you.

00:09:14.669 --> 00:09:19.369
He asked me if I knew who you really are.
He said, "He's Johnny Bravo."

00:09:20.367 --> 00:09:22.478
I told him, well said,
Drago, that's exactly it.

00:09:22.655 --> 00:09:24.535
So, you're Johnny Bravo.

00:09:24.721 --> 00:09:27.296
There's something else
I'm curious about.

00:09:29.855 --> 00:09:34.179
Many of my colleagues and players,
when we went abroad to play

00:09:34.352 --> 00:09:37.432
and even Ivanišević confirmed
this a few days ago, they say

00:09:37.564 --> 00:09:42.507
that people from this region
have something special within them.

00:09:42.612 --> 00:09:46.363
We can say it's something unique
to people from the Balkans.

00:09:47.858 --> 00:09:53.138
"You're a mix", your father is
Croatian, your mother is Serbian.

00:09:53.260 --> 00:09:57.194
And on top of that, you're also French.
What have you noticed that we

00:09:57.355 --> 00:10:01.532
Balkan people possess? I mean both
the positives and the negatives.

00:10:01.710 --> 00:10:04.259
And what is it that the French
don't have and vice versa?

00:10:06.780 --> 00:10:11.291
What I can say for sure is
that the French don't have

00:10:16.220 --> 00:10:21.540
that motivation to become
someone in life. To succeed.

00:10:23.060 --> 00:10:28.020
A hunger for success? -Yes, they don't
have that inner hunger for success.

00:10:30.300 --> 00:10:35.420
That's something unique to people
from the Balkans and former Yugoslavia.

00:10:35.780 --> 00:10:41.300
That doesn't exist in France.
Why? I don't know.

00:10:41.500 --> 00:10:50.520
Maybe life conditions are better in France.
Maybe life is easier there.

00:10:51.500 --> 00:10:55.340
They have more options?
-Yes, maybe they have more options.

00:10:55.700 --> 00:11:00.540
I can't say for certain what it is.
If we look at the downside of that,

00:11:00.820 --> 00:11:05.540
it's great to have that in sports,
but maybe it's something that even

00:11:05.750 --> 00:11:09.593
led to the war in the Balkans.
To the breakup of former Yugoslavia.

00:11:09.659 --> 00:11:12.670
You think we're too emotional?
-Yes, we're too emotional

00:11:12.963 --> 00:11:19.460
and we have strong egos.
That's something positive to have

00:11:21.100 --> 00:11:27.820
if you're doing sports
or business, in your work,

00:11:28.700 --> 00:11:33.660
but when you step outside of all of
that, it's not always the best thing.

00:11:33.790 --> 00:11:37.262
That's why I've tried to learn
about myself and about ego,

00:11:37.511 --> 00:11:40.671
and I've noticed that it's not
always the best approach for life

00:11:40.862 --> 00:11:46.255
and relationships with others.
I think a big difference exists there.

00:11:46.460 --> 00:11:52.247
I've often asked myself why the greatest
athletes of all time, in every sport,

00:11:52.433 --> 00:11:55.633
except for rugby
because the ball is different,

00:11:55.819 --> 00:11:58.939
come from the former Yugoslavia.

00:11:59.243 --> 00:12:09.043
When you look at it now, but also
even before, Đoković, Dončić, anyone...

00:12:11.220 --> 00:12:16.380
Jokić... -Yes, Jokić. Also in water
polo, tennis, football with Modrić...

00:12:17.420 --> 00:12:21.460
In all these major sports,
one of the best players in the world

00:12:21.660 --> 00:12:25.280
has always come from this region,
the former Yugoslavia.

00:12:25.467 --> 00:12:30.303
There's definitely something more to it,
of course, it's what we've talked about,

00:12:30.738 --> 00:12:38.335
how they respect sports there,
how sports are integrated into schools,

00:12:38.580 --> 00:12:41.900
how they teach technique,
tactics, and training.

00:12:42.104 --> 00:12:44.384
But sport is something more there,

00:12:44.592 --> 00:12:49.912
it gives you a chance to get out and
become someone, and that drives you.

00:12:50.340 --> 00:12:54.860
That's great in sport,
but outside of sport,

00:12:55.100 --> 00:12:59.300
in everyday life
and in human relationships,

00:12:59.542 --> 00:13:04.462
it might not always be
the best way to live.

00:13:05.780 --> 00:13:08.580
Here, unfortunately,
that's becoming less and less.

00:13:08.940 --> 00:13:12.100
There's less and less
sport in schools...

00:13:12.380 --> 00:13:17.900
I also noticed something
that the journalist from L'Équipe

00:13:18.100 --> 00:13:21.900
pointed out a few years ago, and
I've formed an opinion around that.

00:13:23.340 --> 00:13:27.460
He said something that doesn't quite fit
with elite athletes, the greatest ones,

00:13:27.622 --> 00:13:30.299
because they have an ego, you have
an ego, too - you're a champion,

00:13:30.460 --> 00:13:37.335
you're in that category. He said that
Karabatić's career lasted so long,

00:13:37.678 --> 00:13:40.420
but it also evolved over time.

00:13:40.705 --> 00:13:47.505
Nikola, in the beginning, was an
individual scoring goals, a real scorer.

00:13:49.700 --> 00:13:54.820
Then, when he was at Kiel with Noka,
and later with the national team

00:13:55.060 --> 00:13:59.660
after the departure of the greats
in 2012, he became a leader,

00:14:00.420 --> 00:14:02.500
an organizer, a captain.

00:14:02.740 --> 00:14:05.620
To be a leader and a captain,
you need to give something to your team.

00:14:05.900 --> 00:14:09.620
You don't score 10 points per game
anymore, you score 7,

00:14:09.860 --> 00:14:14.420
but you make them score 4 instead of 2.
And then they respect you more,

00:14:14.620 --> 00:14:17.500
and the chemistry is better.
This isn't just your case,

00:14:17.700 --> 00:14:22.580
it's similar to what Phil Jackson did
when Michael Jordan came to Chicago.

00:14:23.020 --> 00:14:28.180
And then, toward the end of his career,
after injuries, during the Olympics,

00:14:28.540 --> 00:14:36.300
when young players came in, he accepted
the role of not playing the whole game,

00:14:37.860 --> 00:14:41.900
realizing he wasn't the best anymore,
but he was still the most important.

00:14:42.220 --> 00:14:46.940
He was the main guy when it got tough on
the court, in both defense and offense.

00:14:47.220 --> 00:14:51.060
So, it's similar to Modrić's role
now at Real Madrid, right?

00:14:51.300 --> 00:14:55.820
That's great,
but it's also hard to accept.

00:14:59.060 --> 00:15:02.060
Exactly, that's what makes sport great.

00:15:02.260 --> 00:15:04.580
It teaches you that one moment
you're the world champion,

00:15:04.780 --> 00:15:07.980
and the next moment you're losing a cup
against a second-league team,

00:15:08.180 --> 00:15:14.020
and you're not the best anymore.
Sport teaches you that life is like that,

00:15:14.220 --> 00:15:16.820
you're on top one moment,
and then nothing the next.

00:15:17.060 --> 00:15:20.820
One moment you're great, and the next,
your father isn't with you anymore.

00:15:21.060 --> 00:15:24.620
Sport teaches you that you
have to constantly evolve

00:15:25.740 --> 00:15:30.736
and adapt to new situations.
That's something I've learned now.

00:15:30.904 --> 00:15:33.963
When I was younger,
I didn't understand that,

00:15:34.230 --> 00:15:37.430
but as time goes by,
you start to learn these things.

00:15:37.599 --> 00:15:40.879
And it comes down to
what we talked about earlier,

00:15:40.985 --> 00:15:43.891
you learn that you're not
the same player anymore,

00:15:44.078 --> 00:15:46.178
that your role in the team is
no longer the same.

00:15:46.488 --> 00:15:50.881
You learn to let your ego change,
and to find new motivations.

00:15:50.990 --> 00:15:53.350
That's how I've learned
throughout my entire career.

00:15:53.503 --> 00:15:57.335
Of course, when I first came,
I was just a kid, I had to prove myself

00:15:57.517 --> 00:16:00.477
so that the older players
would accept me.

00:16:00.687 --> 00:16:04.006
All those players
whose posters I had on my walls,

00:16:04.157 --> 00:16:06.797
I had to prove to them
that I was the best.

00:16:06.920 --> 00:16:10.760
I didn't say anything, I just gave my
all on the field and in training

00:16:10.983 --> 00:16:16.063
so that they would accept me and I could
prove I deserved to be part of the team.

00:16:16.420 --> 00:16:20.900
Then you prove yourself, and you start
becoming a good individual player,

00:16:21.420 --> 00:16:26.661
you score goals, win titles,
and gain importance.

00:16:28.114 --> 00:16:30.958
Others listen to you,
you become a leader,

00:16:31.192 --> 00:16:35.380
and you realize that your behavior isn't
just about what you give on the field,

00:16:35.580 --> 00:16:40.340
but off the field too. That discipline
you set for yourself encourages others.

00:16:40.500 --> 00:16:44.700
You realize that being
a good player is great,

00:16:45.060 --> 00:16:52.660
but when you see you can help
your teammates play well too,

00:16:52.900 --> 00:16:57.540
that's an even stronger feeling.
I've learned this way.

00:16:57.780 --> 00:17:02.420
Then I turned 37,
suffered a ligament injury,

00:17:02.620 --> 00:17:06.260
and when I came back to the court,
I wasn't the same player anymore.

00:17:06.660 --> 00:17:11.620
New players had joined the team, and
they also wanted to prove themselves.

00:17:12.100 --> 00:17:16.260
That's when you learn to
take on a different role,

00:17:16.980 --> 00:17:19.220
realizing that you are
no longer the captain,

00:17:19.420 --> 00:17:22.700
and someone else is
taking that position.

00:17:22.831 --> 00:17:25.231
Then you learn to put
your ego aside a little bit,

00:17:25.385 --> 00:17:27.785
and if you want to play
for another two or three years,

00:17:27.954 --> 00:17:30.354
you have to adapt to
these new situations.

00:17:30.535 --> 00:17:35.422
You either think, "I'm Nikola Karabatić,
on the team I need to be the best

00:17:35.540 --> 00:17:40.242
and most important player," or you say,
"I'm Karabatić, I'm getting older,

00:17:40.740 --> 00:17:48.580
new players have arrived, they deserve
their moment, and now I help them."

00:17:49.060 --> 00:17:55.100
So, you constantly have to evolve
and adapt to the situations.

00:17:55.460 --> 00:17:59.980
The sooner you realize this, the better
you'll live through your career

00:18:00.180 --> 00:18:06.020
and after it, the transition out
of your career into a new life,

00:18:06.740 --> 00:18:11.700
where you're no longer a player...
I've achieved a lot, experienced a lot,

00:18:11.980 --> 00:18:15.220
and that's great, but I'm no
longer a handball player,

00:18:15.460 --> 00:18:19.900
and I have to learn how that can help me
move forward and live a better life.

00:18:20.540 --> 00:18:23.380
It's a constant process.

00:18:24.260 --> 00:18:28.340
You must constantly develop,
both as a player and as a person.

00:18:28.580 --> 00:18:30.460
Fantastically said.

00:18:31.180 --> 00:18:34.660
But it wasn't easy for you either,
it's not something simple.

00:18:34.980 --> 00:18:38.300
And throughout your career,
you've seen a lot of examples of

00:18:38.500 --> 00:18:40.500
"the bigger the player,
the bigger the ego,"

00:18:40.700 --> 00:18:43.780
where they don't want to
accept their decline.

00:18:44.020 --> 00:18:46.940
The best example of this
would be Ronaldo,

00:18:47.140 --> 00:18:49.380
who still struggles to be
substituted by his coach

00:18:49.620 --> 00:18:52.980
because he believes
he should still play 90 minutes,

00:18:53.220 --> 00:18:56.420
thinking he plays like he used to,
but that's not the reality...

00:18:57.860 --> 00:18:59.380
Fantastically said...

00:18:59.620 --> 00:19:03.340
Yes, and when you watch that,
you learn something from other athletes,

00:19:03.620 --> 00:19:08.740
how they react, and so on. For example,
Ronaldo is an excellent player,

00:19:10.020 --> 00:19:14.620
and I would prefer to watch
Ronaldo at Manchester,

00:19:14.940 --> 00:19:17.380
playing half of the game
or every other game,

00:19:17.580 --> 00:19:20.420
but still playing and helping others.

00:19:20.620 --> 00:19:23.420
Maybe not scoring three goals
every match, but scoring one goal

00:19:23.660 --> 00:19:27.420
or providing an assist,
contributing to the team's success,

00:19:27.700 --> 00:19:33.620
adapting to a new role
instead of going to Saudi Arabia.

00:19:35.460 --> 00:19:41.206
Another important thing is learning to
be open, watching how others work,

00:19:41.402 --> 00:19:48.769
getting inspired, noticing what you
might not like, what doesn't suit you,

00:19:49.472 --> 00:19:53.180
and then adapting.
My path has been what it is...

00:19:53.740 --> 00:20:01.820
When you get a physical injury,
it's also an injury to your ego.

00:20:02.300 --> 00:20:07.900
Until I was 37, I never had any serious
injuries, I thought I was a machine,

00:20:08.500 --> 00:20:12.180
that I could go through my whole career
without any major injuries.

00:20:12.820 --> 00:20:15.140
I came back from the COVID break,

00:20:15.380 --> 00:20:19.540
where I was, for four months, in the
best shape of my life at 37 years old,

00:20:19.740 --> 00:20:23.180
and then I injured my ACL.
Two weeks after the surgery,

00:20:23.420 --> 00:20:26.460
I got a thrombosis
and a pulmonary embolism.

00:20:26.589 --> 00:20:28.909
That's when the ego comes in,
it shrinks.

00:20:29.015 --> 00:20:32.135
You realize you're small... -Yes,
you realize you're not untouchable,

00:20:32.227 --> 00:20:34.987
that I could've stayed in the hospital,
that I could've died...

00:20:35.107 --> 00:20:37.789
From those experiences, you also learn,
and when you return to the field,

00:20:37.901 --> 00:20:39.642
you have a different energy.

00:20:39.715 --> 00:20:43.036
You're happy and positive
that you can still play handball.

00:20:43.260 --> 00:20:46.060
You get that new energy
and motivation...

00:20:46.300 --> 00:20:54.361
You're constantly learning from those
moments that brought you down to earth,

00:20:54.775 --> 00:20:58.220
but made you stronger, maybe not
as a player, but as a person.

00:20:58.380 --> 00:21:04.300
Or maybe you don't learn anything, and
those situations just repeat themselves.

00:21:04.722 --> 00:21:10.499
You have to learn from every opportunity
life or your career presents

00:21:11.289 --> 00:21:16.220
and become better as a player
or as a person.

00:21:17.620 --> 00:21:19.620
Gosh, I mean...

00:21:20.260 --> 00:21:24.557
This is the first time we're meeting,
but I have to say I'm impressed.

00:21:24.798 --> 00:21:28.448
You're incredibly strong in your mind,
it feels like I'm reading a book about

00:21:28.636 --> 00:21:37.177
"How You Should Behave" or talking
to a psychologist. I really admire you!

00:21:37.951 --> 00:21:43.255
Tell me, how did you handle losses?

00:21:45.740 --> 00:21:50.100
For example, did you suffer,
did you blame yourself?

00:21:50.380 --> 00:21:54.180
There's a period in your life,
which may be a coincidence,

00:21:54.340 --> 00:21:57.940
but I'm sure one thing
affected the other...

00:21:58.220 --> 00:22:06.180
It was quite a turbulent year.
2011, you lost your father, right?

00:22:06.420 --> 00:22:10.260
Then in 2012,
that scandal happened.

00:22:10.460 --> 00:22:15.620
And 2013 was the only year
the championship wasn't won.

00:22:15.940 --> 00:22:22.500
You were... Were you disappointed
in people? Did you "break," as they say?

00:22:22.820 --> 00:22:28.020
Some in the public criticized you,
not like "he hit the post,"

00:22:29.180 --> 00:22:34.580
but personal and nasty things.
I noticed you approached it strongly.

00:22:34.860 --> 00:22:40.620
You even said, "I see this as a match
I must win. I will prove it."

00:22:40.780 --> 00:22:44.700
Did your mindset help you
and how did you feel back then?

00:22:44.940 --> 00:22:51.340
Yes, exactly. My mindset
back then helped me a lot,

00:22:52.020 --> 00:22:56.340
because I thought I was facing
the hardest thing in life.

00:22:56.580 --> 00:23:00.980
My father was gone.
He meant everything to me.

00:23:01.620 --> 00:23:06.820
It was tough, but at the same time,
when something like that happens,

00:23:06.980 --> 00:23:12.740
people love you, they're there for you.
If anything happens in life,

00:23:12.980 --> 00:23:16.420
we're here to help.
-They feel for you.

00:23:16.780 --> 00:23:21.900
It's hard, but people love you.
A year later, the scandal breaks

00:23:22.140 --> 00:23:25.740
and everyone hates me.
I'm not allowed to play handball.

00:23:25.980 --> 00:23:30.780
Then you see that a year ago
everyone loved you, wanted to help,

00:23:31.060 --> 00:23:36.580
and a year later, they hate you,
wish you the worst.

00:23:37.460 --> 00:23:42.100
You learn a lot from that.
What helped me? What you said.

00:23:42.340 --> 00:23:46.020
I saw a new challenge in that,
a new game to win.

00:23:46.260 --> 00:23:50.140
Now I'll prove this
can't break me. I'll be even better.

00:23:50.472 --> 00:23:54.826
That's how I worked back then.
When I was younger,

00:23:55.651 --> 00:24:01.998
losing hit me hard.
I cried, I felt horrible.

00:24:03.709 --> 00:24:05.720
It was really tough.

00:24:06.221 --> 00:24:11.568
Over the years I learned how
to handle losses.

00:24:11.939 --> 00:24:17.568
At that time I thought like this:
It's a new challenge, new game,

00:24:17.857 --> 00:24:20.756
I have to prove I'm better
and I'll become even better.

00:24:21.021 --> 00:24:29.858
That's how I functioned, but I also
realized it drained my energy.

00:24:30.514 --> 00:24:37.261
When you think and play like that,
it brings a lot of negative energy.

00:24:37.523 --> 00:24:41.243
I always wondered
why it happened to me,

00:24:41.567 --> 00:24:45.127
why it's not fair
people don't like me.

00:24:45.500 --> 00:24:51.540
You read the news and see lies.
It hurts because every night

00:24:51.860 --> 00:24:56.540
you carry that negative energy
to bed, and it pushes you

00:24:56.820 --> 00:25:02.460
to prove you're the best
the next day, but it pulls you down.

00:25:02.980 --> 00:25:08.009
Over time I learned to leave
all that aside,

00:25:08.524 --> 00:25:13.334
that hatred I carried inside,
that pushed me to become

00:25:13.802 --> 00:25:19.099
even better and to return.
I worked hard to suppress it,

00:25:19.189 --> 00:25:25.170
to understand why it all happened,
what was behind it,

00:25:25.751 --> 00:25:30.391
why Montpellier acted that way,
why the media wrote that way.

00:25:32.767 --> 00:25:38.548
To not... how do you say...
-To forgive them.

00:25:38.980 --> 00:25:45.140
Not to forgive, to understand,
to accept it and not live with hate.

00:25:45.780 --> 00:25:55.340
I worked hard on myself so it
wouldn't... -Eat at you for life.

00:25:56.180 --> 00:26:01.300
Many would've broken.
These are huge things lasting years.

00:26:01.580 --> 00:26:07.428
It's two years when you sum it up.
-Yes, it lasts... -And at first...

00:26:07.644 --> 00:26:14.879
At first, it eats you up
and then you come out stronger.

00:26:15.220 --> 00:26:19.900
It's like a game, a challenge.
As time passes,

00:26:20.140 --> 00:26:25.500
you see it gnaws at you, annoys you,
your reactions aren't good.

00:26:25.980 --> 00:26:32.499
If you want to live positive and normal,
you have to push it aside and accept it,

00:26:33.719 --> 00:26:38.799
and move on. Now I think
if it didn't happen to me,

00:26:39.078 --> 00:26:45.758
I wouldn't be here now, nor would I
have had such a career.

00:26:46.460 --> 00:26:51.940
I wouldn't be happy today,
nor would we talk about it.

00:26:52.180 --> 00:26:57.620
It helped me and now I look
at it from a distance

00:26:57.980 --> 00:27:01.220
as something positive
that happened to me.

00:27:01.460 --> 00:27:09.540
From that ugly situation something
good came out. -Well said.

00:27:11.340 --> 00:27:15.707
Those sporting failures -
your career is impressive,

00:27:15.974 --> 00:27:18.941
of course, there were losses.
But what are they, really?

00:27:19.500 --> 00:27:26.420
You didn't win the Champions League
with Paris, or the last Olympics -

00:27:27.660 --> 00:27:34.660
would've been ideal to end it like that?
-I don't know what was hardest.

00:27:36.580 --> 00:27:43.460
Of course, if we'd won with PSG,
the Champions League, amazing.

00:27:44.340 --> 00:27:51.820
Could you have? -We were in the final,
lost to Vardar in the last second.

00:27:52.140 --> 00:27:56.580
Čupić scored. Of course it's hard.

00:27:56.780 --> 00:28:00.260
At the Olympics, losing like that
in the quarterfinals...

00:28:00.420 --> 00:28:04.580
You're up by two with 15 seconds left.
That can't happen. But it did.

00:28:05.540 --> 00:28:10.900
It's so hard, that's what sport is.

00:28:11.580 --> 00:28:15.580
At the same time, I worked so much
on myself and learned to see

00:28:15.820 --> 00:28:19.900
things from another angle.
I never thought I'd...

00:28:20.140 --> 00:28:25.860
As a kid, I wanted to play for my country
and be the best in the world.

00:28:26.140 --> 00:28:31.820
Looking back on what I've achieved,
I can't complain - and shouldn't.

00:28:32.100 --> 00:28:35.540
It's very hard to end a career
with that kind of loss,

00:28:35.980 --> 00:28:41.005
in front of all of France.
How many were in Lille?

00:28:41.225 --> 00:28:45.497
In the stadium, 28 thousand people.
Family, friends, everyone.

00:28:45.810 --> 00:28:51.050
That was very hard, but I also had
so many amazing moments,

00:28:51.580 --> 00:28:58.620
I wouldn't trade it. That too was
a challenge - to end my career

00:28:58.860 --> 00:29:05.860
with that kind of loss.
But it pushed me to work on myself.

00:29:06.220 --> 00:29:14.513
I can't carry that disappointment
into a new life.

00:29:15.422 --> 00:29:20.262
That pushed me to grow.
I wouldn't change it.

00:29:20.580 --> 00:29:23.700
Of course I'd be happy
if I'd won a medal...

00:29:23.900 --> 00:29:30.900
But you can't have it all. -If I had,
maybe I'd be Minister of Sport now.

00:29:31.006 --> 00:29:33.566
That wouldn't be good for me.

00:29:35.060 --> 00:29:40.380
It's amazing how you grow
in your career and in your mind.

00:29:40.660 --> 00:29:48.660
How did you feel as a young player?
You said in 2003 Onesta took you

00:29:48.900 --> 00:29:55.527
to the championship, but you didn't play?
-Yes. -You were just there.

00:29:55.676 --> 00:29:58.620
What did you think? Did you think
you could play,

00:29:58.820 --> 00:30:04.353
or were you just impressed to be there?
You'd already won the Champions League.

00:30:04.650 --> 00:30:10.814
That was before. -A year before?
-Onesta took me to the tournament.

00:30:11.360 --> 00:30:18.228
I was injured right before.
He said, "You'll go to Portugal."

00:30:20.580 --> 00:30:31.467
I'd be the 16th player - he named 15
and if a goalie got hurt, I'd be in.

00:30:32.701 --> 00:30:37.834
That's what he told me,
and as a kid I was just happy.

00:30:38.020 --> 00:30:42.588
Going to a championship at 18,
a dream come true.

00:30:42.828 --> 00:30:47.148
After two games the goalie didn't
get hurt, Croatia beat France,

00:30:47.278 --> 00:30:52.260
and the team was in chaos.
Onesta didn't put me on the roster.

00:30:52.377 --> 00:30:56.165
I waited. Maybe the next match?
No. Maybe one more? No.

00:30:56.436 --> 00:31:02.196
He never added me. I played
the bronze medal match.

00:31:02.562 --> 00:31:05.994
I warmed up with the team,
then he put me back in the stands.

00:31:06.208 --> 00:31:08.808
But I got a medal.
He didn't say a word.

00:31:09.033 --> 00:31:13.869
At 18, of course, you don't
ask the coach why you didn't play.

00:31:14.900 --> 00:31:19.740
Next match he didn't call me either.
That was a friendly vs Germany.

00:31:20.020 --> 00:31:23.100
But J. Fernandez got injured,
and he called me up.

00:31:23.460 --> 00:31:26.820
I scored 10 goals. -Right away.

00:31:27.060 --> 00:31:30.180
He couldn't take me
off the list anymore.

00:31:31.100 --> 00:31:38.667
It was hard and I didn't understand.
Now I do, because it was hard.

00:31:39.019 --> 00:31:43.260
The coach was new, under pressure,
they lost to Croatia.

00:31:43.460 --> 00:31:48.940
Maybe he didn't want to include me
so I wouldn't be the one to save France.

00:31:49.460 --> 00:31:54.780
He was afraid of my start.
I felt like he feared me,

00:31:55.020 --> 00:32:02.780
that I might disrupt the team,
the relationships with older players.

00:32:03.700 --> 00:32:08.620
He feared a lot of things.
We didn't have the best relationship at first.

00:32:09.020 --> 00:32:16.797
Later it got better. In 2003,
that hit me pretty hard,

00:32:17.500 --> 00:32:22.020
but it gave me more motivation
to prove myself because he

00:32:22.540 --> 00:32:26.860
didn't want me in the team...
-And that's motivation too.

00:32:27.000 --> 00:32:29.172
In the end, you see everything
as motivation.

00:32:30.300 --> 00:32:33.860
It's fascinating, that's the best,
but it's not easy.

00:32:34.220 --> 00:32:38.300
You turn everything into motivation,
everything you can.

00:32:39.020 --> 00:32:42.460
You turn it into a challenge,
not something to stop you,

00:32:42.700 --> 00:32:48.420
mess up your head or confidence.
That's great, Nikola. Well done.

00:32:48.700 --> 00:32:54.060
We have to talk about handball.
I'm no expert, but I watch handball.

00:32:54.300 --> 00:32:58.900
When the big tournaments happen,
it's not just the handball world.

00:32:59.460 --> 00:33:05.140
The whole sports world
focuses on handball.

00:33:05.460 --> 00:33:11.787
It's a simple sport, I think.
Very physically demanding.

00:33:11.959 --> 00:33:14.599
There are constant duels,
always pushing.

00:33:14.938 --> 00:33:17.298
But it's not about brutality.

00:33:17.677 --> 00:33:22.083
I think there's not enough speed
for anything to happen

00:33:22.359 --> 00:33:27.318
when speed and mass meet.
It feels more like wrestling.

00:33:28.940 --> 00:33:39.260
But it's exhausting. -Games are not
exhausting or the rough play or contact.

00:33:39.900 --> 00:33:44.140
The hardest part of handball
is the playing rhythm.

00:33:44.340 --> 00:33:48.060
When you play for PSG,
in Kiel, in Barcelona,

00:33:48.260 --> 00:33:52.340
in a tough league, the Champions League,
for the national team...

00:33:52.580 --> 00:33:56.860
You're playing every third day -
that's 70 matches a year.

00:33:58.740 --> 00:34:00.874
With the national team,
each year you play either

00:34:00.976 --> 00:34:03.136
the European or World Championship.
And when it's the Olympics,

00:34:03.290 --> 00:34:05.616
you have the European Championship,
the World Championship,

00:34:05.740 --> 00:34:08.015
and Olympics all in one year.
That's the hardest part.

00:34:08.140 --> 00:34:11.624
Every third day you play, travel...
You know how it is-you travel,

00:34:11.800 --> 00:34:15.093
you play, you come back...
You have to win every match.

00:34:15.281 --> 00:34:18.601
And that's the toughest part, because
that match rhythm never stops.

00:34:18.756 --> 00:34:21.276
Except when you get injured,
you never get a break.

00:34:21.335 --> 00:34:23.381
And that's the hardest thing.

00:34:23.573 --> 00:34:26.853
Of course there's contact in handball,
but our sport isn't rugby,

00:34:27.180 --> 00:34:31.860
where players hit each other
and it's very violent.

00:34:32.627 --> 00:34:39.727
There's physical contact in handball too,
but the rhythm is the tough part.

00:34:40.009 --> 00:34:43.289
You play for the national team, come back,
and the Champions League continues...

00:34:43.419 --> 00:34:47.258
If your league is strong,
like in Germany or France,

00:34:47.418 --> 00:34:54.218
you must be mentally prepared,
motivated - never letting yourself

00:34:54.660 --> 00:35:02.261
fall into the trap of every day
feeling the same, losing drive.

00:35:02.503 --> 00:35:10.730
Physically too, you must be ready
to endure 70 games a year.

00:35:11.145 --> 00:35:13.668
That's why handball is a tough sport.

00:35:13.760 --> 00:35:19.105
This interests me as a coach,
and I asked Ivanišević about it,

00:35:19.580 --> 00:35:21.940
even though tennis is
an individual sport.

00:35:22.260 --> 00:35:27.700
But in handball, at major tournaments,
you often play every day.

00:35:27.900 --> 00:35:31.140
You play day after day.
That's 60 minutes.

00:35:31.263 --> 00:35:34.030
There are rotations, sure, but for example,
you play the whole match,

00:35:34.115 --> 00:35:38.475
Metličić plays the whole match...
That would be impossible in football.

00:35:38.621 --> 00:35:41.147
How can you play every day?

00:35:41.540 --> 00:35:45.020
Yeah, in football that's not possible,
because you run a lot,

00:35:45.620 --> 00:35:49.260
there are many sprints,
the distance is greater...

00:35:49.460 --> 00:35:52.660
But there's less contact.
-Yeah, not much contact.

00:35:52.900 --> 00:35:57.460
In handball, you must be strong...
-The contact wears you down.

00:35:57.660 --> 00:36:03.903
... physically, so you can endure it,
so the contact doesn't drain you.

00:36:04.184 --> 00:36:11.180
You must be mindful of everything
and be physically prepared.

00:36:11.940 --> 00:36:16.100
What helped me was that
I was always physically ready.

00:36:16.340 --> 00:36:20.820
My father always told me
that it's not enough

00:36:21.020 --> 00:36:23.420
to just be the best at handball.

00:36:23.700 --> 00:36:27.940
If you want to be successful,
you must be physically ready too.

00:36:28.180 --> 00:36:31.980
If there's running,
you must be the best at that too,

00:36:32.340 --> 00:36:36.140
also in the gym, in school...
If you're smart,

00:36:36.340 --> 00:36:41.560
you'll understand situations
and grow properly.

00:36:43.500 --> 00:36:47.260
So that's also very important
for every athlete.

00:36:47.460 --> 00:36:50.867
You must understand
that talent alone isn't enough.

00:36:50.970 --> 00:36:54.869
It has to be the whole package.
In football, handball, basketball -

00:36:54.965 --> 00:36:56.845
everything you do matters.

00:36:57.145 --> 00:37:02.545
Sometimes, hard work and discipline
are more important than talent.

00:37:04.820 --> 00:37:10.180
That's especially true in handball
if you want to reach a high level.

00:37:10.420 --> 00:37:15.100
If you play in the first league,
you'll need to play

00:37:16.220 --> 00:37:18.820
at least 30 games a season,
and that's already tough.

00:37:19.020 --> 00:37:20.740
And that's great.

00:37:20.980 --> 00:37:25.020
But if you want to reach the next level
and play 70 games a season,

00:37:25.220 --> 00:37:30.540
then you must invest
in all those areas.

00:37:32.140 --> 00:37:37.220
What kind of impact does
the coach have,

00:37:37.420 --> 00:37:40.940
not the coach as a group leader,
but tactically?

00:37:41.580 --> 00:37:46.980
Here, we talk a lot and debate
about 6:0, 5:1, 3:2 defenses...

00:37:47.180 --> 00:37:51.020
Is that really important and
decisive, or is the group

00:37:51.220 --> 00:37:53.820
and the transition game more
crucial in today's handball,

00:37:54.052 --> 00:37:56.852
where it's constantly
running back and forth?

00:37:57.046 --> 00:38:00.497
There's this story - actually,
not an anecdote but a real story -

00:38:00.643 --> 00:38:04.482
that during the Rio Olympics,
in the semifinal against Germany,

00:38:04.609 --> 00:38:07.209
when they caught up
after you had a big lead,

00:38:07.363 --> 00:38:12.716
you called a timeout and asked
for a play you hadn't used in years.

00:38:17.540 --> 00:38:22.460
What I love about handball
is the tactics.

00:38:24.615 --> 00:38:28.500
My father helped me a lot with that,
because he was a goalkeeper.

00:38:28.740 --> 00:38:31.900
When I went to Montpellier,
I learned a lot there,

00:38:32.180 --> 00:38:36.980
but I really learned precision,
technique, and tactics with Noka.

00:38:39.260 --> 00:38:44.780
It's like playing chess. You follow
where each player is positioned,

00:38:44.980 --> 00:38:48.740
and even though you don't
have the ball, your position

00:38:48.940 --> 00:38:51.620
on the court is very important.
Because if you move a little,

00:38:51.820 --> 00:38:55.500
you create more space
for your center back and left wing...

00:38:55.900 --> 00:38:59.580
Everything you do on the court
has significance. -It has its purpose.

00:38:59.820 --> 00:39:05.420
I learned so much from Noka,
that I learned to think that way

00:39:05.860 --> 00:39:11.260
and continued to pass it on
to the guys on the national team.

00:39:11.500 --> 00:39:15.020
So, I had a lot of responsibility
on the national team.

00:39:15.260 --> 00:39:18.580
And that timeout against Germany.

00:39:18.980 --> 00:39:23.900
It often happened that the coach
would call a timeout

00:39:24.006 --> 00:39:27.615
and say something, and I would
suggest something else.

00:39:28.568 --> 00:39:37.529
I was always lucky that the coaches
respected and valued my input.

00:39:37.809 --> 00:39:42.877
After that timeout, we changed
the game and tried a new tactic.

00:39:43.140 --> 00:39:49.740
Danijel looked at me and asked
if I was sure, because he was supposed

00:39:49.980 --> 00:39:52.340
to shoot from the right back position.

00:39:52.580 --> 00:39:57.540
I told him I was sure and that he'd score
100% if he did it that way.

00:39:57.820 --> 00:40:01.740
We executed the play, and he scored.
Now, when I look at that play,

00:40:01.940 --> 00:40:05.300
I see we didn't do it perfectly,
but we still managed to score.

00:40:07.969 --> 00:40:11.409
And I'm proud of that too.

00:40:11.593 --> 00:40:14.319
That means you'll be a coach.
You'll be a coach.

00:40:14.540 --> 00:40:20.340
When our players, the media, the fans,
everyone, talk about the difference

00:40:20.620 --> 00:40:28.580
between France and Croatia at that time,
they usually mention Omeyer.

00:40:29.780 --> 00:40:33.820
Everyone says how well he defends.
Yes, he defended the best against us.

00:40:34.020 --> 00:40:37.580
How crucial is the role
of the goalkeeper in handball?

00:40:37.820 --> 00:40:40.700
Extremely crucial.
If you ask goalkeepers,

00:40:40.900 --> 00:40:47.020
they'll tell you they're responsible
for 80% of the team's results.

00:40:48.860 --> 00:40:53.020
Later, we joke about it
because that's not really true.

00:40:53.700 --> 00:40:58.605
We witnessed this at the Olympics
when our goalkeeper, Vincent Gerard,

00:40:58.736 --> 00:41:02.699
had about 40% saves,
and we still lost the match.

00:41:02.951 --> 00:41:06.831
So I always tell goalkeepers
that what they claim isn't really true.

00:41:07.039 --> 00:41:10.599
But a good goalkeeper
makes a huge difference,

00:41:10.886 --> 00:41:16.926
and we had Omeyer, and thanks
to him, we won so much.

00:41:18.860 --> 00:41:22.580
We learned a lot from that,
because it really impacts your ego.

00:41:22.694 --> 00:41:25.107
You always think you're
the most important person on the team.

00:41:25.174 --> 00:41:27.013
You think everything depends on you.

00:41:27.111 --> 00:41:30.216
Of course, that's not just your achievement,
because handball is a team sport.

00:41:30.300 --> 00:41:34.235
That's also what I love about handball,
because you can never succeed alone.

00:41:34.260 --> 00:41:40.220
Omeyer was a fantastic goalkeeper,
the best goalkeeper of all time.

00:41:41.660 --> 00:41:47.100
If he had played for another team,
maybe we wouldn't have won so many titles.

00:41:47.420 --> 00:41:50.580
If you look at Denmark,
you'll see they achieved

00:41:50.980 --> 00:41:53.940
a lot of success thanks
to their goalkeeper.

00:41:54.180 --> 00:41:58.340
They had Landin, and now they have
Nielsen, who plays for Barcelona.

00:41:58.540 --> 00:42:02.020
Those are two of the best
goalkeepers in the world.

00:42:02.260 --> 00:42:06.060
Their results are really
closely tied to the goalkeeper.

00:42:06.300 --> 00:42:10.180
Did your father,
as a former goalkeeper, help you?

00:42:10.420 --> 00:42:15.475
Did he suggest that you better understand
what the goalkeeper is thinking?

00:42:16.860 --> 00:42:23.911
We always talked on the phone
the day before the match,

00:42:24.193 --> 00:42:26.762
when I played in Kiel or anywhere else.

00:42:28.711 --> 00:42:31.122
My father would talk to me
about the goalkeeper.

00:42:31.290 --> 00:42:35.442
For example: "That goalkeeper is Danish
or Swedish, he dives down.

00:42:35.723 --> 00:42:41.567
Try to lift the ball when you shoot,
or make the ball bounce off the floor."

00:42:42.260 --> 00:42:46.420
So, we always talked about that,
and those analyses with him

00:42:47.140 --> 00:42:50.820
were a form of preparation for me.

00:42:52.100 --> 00:42:55.340
Mental preparation
and work on technique.

00:42:55.540 --> 00:42:57.340
That helped me a lot.

00:42:57.660 --> 00:42:59.900
Your father had special methods.

00:43:00.180 --> 00:43:05.420
I read that when you were little,
and this later helped you,

00:43:05.620 --> 00:43:10.140
not only to be a shooter but also a leader,
he wouldn't let you shoot in training.

00:43:10.380 --> 00:43:13.300
You always had to assist
with the ball. -Yes, I had to.

00:43:13.500 --> 00:43:17.500
He always gave me certain exercises.

00:43:18.620 --> 00:43:21.420
For example: "You can't score a goal,
but if you want to win,

00:43:21.620 --> 00:43:24.780
every player on your team
must score at least one goal."

00:43:24.980 --> 00:43:27.620
You have to make sure
everyone scores at least once.

00:43:27.860 --> 00:43:31.500
Or: "You can't play with your right hand,
only pass and shoot with your left."

00:43:31.700 --> 00:43:36.460
He would always throw in
some exercises while I was training,

00:43:36.660 --> 00:43:39.540
so I could develop even more.

00:43:40.780 --> 00:43:44.620
Alright, tell me something
more about handball...

00:43:44.900 --> 00:43:50.220
It seems to me that it's quite connected
to smaller places.

00:43:50.620 --> 00:43:54.860
Metković, earlier, or Čačak...
No, Šabac Metaloplastika,

00:43:55.260 --> 00:43:59.540
Kiel, Flensburg, and Pamplona...

00:43:59.820 --> 00:44:04.420
It was less connected to Hamburg,
Paris, Zagreb, Barcelona.

00:44:04.980 --> 00:44:09.660
Is it because it's difficult
to ignite interest in a community

00:44:09.900 --> 00:44:13.140
when there's already football,
basketball, etc.?

00:44:13.540 --> 00:44:23.100
And are you satisfied with the treatment
of handball in the world of sports?

00:44:27.900 --> 00:44:32.260
The fact that handball
wasn't that popular in France

00:44:32.460 --> 00:44:35.460
was also a motivation for me.

00:44:36.100 --> 00:44:39.220
Through what we achieved
and how we played,

00:44:39.500 --> 00:44:42.260
we wanted to spark interest
in handball in France,

00:44:42.500 --> 00:44:45.220
to make it a true sport
and for people to follow and love it.

00:44:45.460 --> 00:44:49.798
That was my goal
and additional motivation.

00:44:50.079 --> 00:44:54.019
And now, when I look at it...
What can I say?

00:44:55.004 --> 00:45:03.357
I would like handball to be bigger
and to receive more recognition.

00:45:04.026 --> 00:45:11.199
But at the same time, I wish, even
though handball is not that popular,

00:45:14.780 --> 00:45:25.180
that my children play it and that it
stays on a smaller level...

00:45:25.380 --> 00:45:29.460
That the sport is played purely
for the sake of sport,

00:45:29.660 --> 00:45:34.780
for mental and physical strength,
and that one learns from it.

00:45:35.020 --> 00:45:44.100
But I see that some people already
expect a professional level in 10 years.

00:45:44.500 --> 00:45:47.740
They talk about money
and business. -Horrible!

00:45:47.980 --> 00:45:51.900
That's why I love this side of sport,
handball is not a business.

00:45:52.540 --> 00:45:58.660
You can make a living from handball,
but you won't become a billionaire.

00:45:59.420 --> 00:46:04.620
But you'll learn a lot from it in life.
And it is a real sport.

00:46:05.700 --> 00:46:08.620
Now that I've gone through all of that,

00:46:09.500 --> 00:46:16.820
I wouldn't want handball
to become like the NBA,

00:46:17.220 --> 00:46:22.780
because handball creates
good people. -Well said.

00:46:22.980 --> 00:46:24.460
I'll ask a few more questions.

00:46:24.940 --> 00:46:28.740
You've been an athlete for a long time
and follow sports?

00:46:28.980 --> 00:46:33.780
You're also a commentator
for the NFL and NBA.

00:46:34.020 --> 00:46:37.420
You don't deny it, you've earned it,

00:46:38.300 --> 00:46:41.740
you're a top-level athlete
who has succeeded.

00:46:41.980 --> 00:46:45.420
Do you think you would've
succeeded in another sport?

00:46:45.620 --> 00:46:51.620
Were you interested in individual sports?
-Yes, I followed almost every sport.

00:46:51.820 --> 00:46:56.100
I followed tennis a lot,
because Luka played tennis.

00:46:56.860 --> 00:46:59.740
I watched Goran win Wimbledon.

00:46:59.940 --> 00:47:03.940
Then Đoković, Nadal, Federer...

00:47:04.140 --> 00:47:08.244
I loved basketball, football,
and volleyball, every sport.

00:47:09.340 --> 00:47:15.260
If my father had played volleyball,
I would've played volleyball too.

00:47:15.420 --> 00:47:18.679
If he had played water polo,
I would've played that too.

00:47:18.953 --> 00:47:26.265
I don't think I chose handball,
life chose that for me.

00:47:27.020 --> 00:47:31.180
And I had the goal of being the best.

00:47:32.060 --> 00:47:38.740
That's why I believe that up
to the age of 40 you live

00:47:39.140 --> 00:47:52.154
what life has chosen for you.
Then you reflect and grow as a person.

00:47:53.140 --> 00:47:58.060
I never really chose handball.
Handball chose me to play for it.

00:48:01.677 --> 00:48:06.687
This is a show for children,
but also for parents.

00:48:07.586 --> 00:48:14.647
How does one become a young
handball player in France?

00:48:14.774 --> 00:48:18.569
Where does it start?
Does it start in school, clubs?

00:48:18.797 --> 00:48:20.757
Do you have something like
a "Center of Information",

00:48:21.020 --> 00:48:25.780
like in football? A regional center
where the best gather and train?

00:48:26.260 --> 00:48:29.940
How does that work?
When do you start training?

00:48:30.580 --> 00:48:35.180
We talked about that earlier.

00:48:36.361 --> 00:48:40.161
In football, when you're the best.
In tennis, by the age of 12 or 13,

00:48:40.401 --> 00:48:43.351
you're already entering that
Center of Information,

00:48:43.540 --> 00:48:47.900
where the best of the best gather.
In France, you play handball normally

00:48:48.100 --> 00:48:54.020
until the age of 15, in your club,
with your coach and your team

00:48:54.700 --> 00:48:58.700
and you build a love for the sport.
Then, if you're among the best,

00:48:58.940 --> 00:49:05.445
you enter that Center of Information,
those regional centers,

00:49:05.982 --> 00:49:08.422
where top talents gather.

00:49:08.567 --> 00:49:14.406
Until 15 you live a normal life.
And that's a huge strength.

00:49:15.100 --> 00:49:17.820
It's not easy when you're 11 or 12

00:49:18.060 --> 00:49:20.140
and you already end up in that
Center of Information.

00:49:20.420 --> 00:49:26.220
Or when you're 13 or 14 and you're
earning more than your PE teacher.

00:49:27.020 --> 00:49:30.860
That's not easy for kids,
nor for parents.

00:49:31.460 --> 00:49:39.100
Many parents live their lives
through their children.

00:49:40.020 --> 00:49:43.043
They try to make up for their own
failures through them.

00:49:43.160 --> 00:49:45.893
This creates pressure on the kids.

00:49:46.340 --> 00:49:50.700
What helped me was that my father
never pressured me

00:49:50.940 --> 00:49:55.740
to be the best in the world or to succeed.
That was something I wanted.

00:49:55.940 --> 00:50:00.901
He always said that brings
a lot of pressure,

00:50:01.643 --> 00:50:06.862
and if I wanted to take that path,
he would help me,

00:50:06.996 --> 00:50:09.518
but if I didn't succeed,
he would still love me,

00:50:09.726 --> 00:50:12.818
even if I didn't become
a top handball player.

00:50:13.076 --> 00:50:16.116
What mattered was that I was
happy in life.

00:50:17.020 --> 00:50:20.460
That's very important for children.

00:50:20.700 --> 00:50:24.330
That they're proud of their kids
and the sport they choose.

00:50:24.440 --> 00:50:28.095
Sport is important,
because it's a school of life.

00:50:28.380 --> 00:50:35.271
You can learn so much in a team
with a coach, with teammates,

00:50:35.521 --> 00:50:43.356
opponents, referees,
both mentally and physically.

00:50:44.140 --> 00:50:48.466
Of course, if you succeed as
a professional athlete, that's great,

00:50:48.660 --> 00:50:52.180
but sport should be practiced.

00:50:52.380 --> 00:50:57.060
All children should be involved,
not only in one sport,

00:50:57.270 --> 00:51:01.550
but in different ones, to choose what
they love and to learn discipline,

00:51:01.900 --> 00:51:04.540
and also to have fun.

00:51:05.060 --> 00:51:10.580
That "Center of Information" is both
a good and a not-so-good thing.

00:51:11.060 --> 00:51:14.700
That's the western way,
putting the best with the best.

00:51:15.020 --> 00:51:18.540
But from the very start,
it creates rivalry.

00:51:18.860 --> 00:51:23.540
But, when everyone is together,
maybe it slows you down,

00:51:23.780 --> 00:51:28.700
so you don't go all the way,
but it creates chemistry and energy,

00:51:28.980 --> 00:51:33.433
and that fifth element, the most
important in team sports and life.

00:51:33.618 --> 00:51:40.160
One more thing. You and Luka
both succeeded in professional sports,

00:51:40.540 --> 00:51:45.613
the sport you're now talking about.
Your parents instilled a strong work ethic

00:51:45.980 --> 00:51:49.300
when it came to school
and gave you a proper upbringing.

00:51:49.540 --> 00:51:54.340
You have two kids, right?
Will you guide them toward sports?

00:51:54.500 --> 00:52:02.500
Would you be more satisfied if they did
amateur rather than professional sports?

00:52:05.620 --> 00:52:11.420
That's a good question.
My son Alec plays handball.

00:52:11.940 --> 00:52:14.220
He also plays basketball and tennis.

00:52:14.500 --> 00:52:17.940
Nora has recently stopped
playing handball.

00:52:18.180 --> 00:52:21.060
She said: "Mom, dad, I don't want
to do this anymore,

00:52:21.300 --> 00:52:25.820
because I'm not good and I'm not
the best. I don't want to continue."

00:52:26.220 --> 00:52:29.380
I try to explain to my children...

00:52:29.700 --> 00:52:32.881
that I'll love them no matter
what they choose to do.

00:52:33.057 --> 00:52:36.817
They don't have to succeed in sports,
they just need to be happy.

00:52:36.972 --> 00:52:44.624
I don't want Alec to play handball
just because I did.

00:52:46.318 --> 00:52:50.894
I know it'll be a hundred times
harder for him than for me.

00:52:51.097 --> 00:52:55.860
My father meant everything to me,
but he wasn't the best in the world.

00:52:56.100 --> 00:52:59.620
I was the best in the world
in handball.

00:52:59.860 --> 00:53:04.660
We live in better conditions now
than when I was a child.

00:53:04.940 --> 00:53:08.740
My parents did everything
to give us a good life.

00:53:09.060 --> 00:53:12.620
But I know it'll be much harder
for him than for me.

00:53:12.900 --> 00:53:17.100
I try to act the way my father
acted with me.

00:53:19.100 --> 00:53:24.100
He gave me direction and taught me
discipline and work ethic,

00:53:25.060 --> 00:53:28.860
so I would understand that
anything is possible in life,

00:53:29.100 --> 00:53:32.980
if you really want it
and work hard for it.

00:53:33.540 --> 00:53:38.220
But at the same time, you must
enjoy life because life is short.

00:53:38.460 --> 00:53:41.020
You never know when it might end.

00:53:41.300 --> 00:53:46.900
I try to pass on everything my mom
and dad taught me to my kids.

00:53:47.460 --> 00:53:50.660
And, of course, I would love
for them to play sports.

00:53:50.900 --> 00:53:53.620
As I said, sport is a school of life.

00:53:54.020 --> 00:54:00.340
If you're involved in sports,
you have a better start in life.

00:54:00.540 --> 00:54:06.060
Are you aware that kids today spend
less time outside playing than you did?

00:54:06.300 --> 00:54:08.540
How do you deal with that?

00:54:08.780 --> 00:54:14.380
Is anything being done in France
to help children have more fun?

00:54:15.660 --> 00:54:20.340
It's a big topic of
"sports in school" in France.

00:54:20.620 --> 00:54:24.140
We have the Olympics here,
and everything is going well.

00:54:24.420 --> 00:54:27.620
Everyone loves the Olympics,
even though many thought

00:54:27.860 --> 00:54:31.380
it wouldn't be good for Paris.

00:54:31.620 --> 00:54:37.140
Now they've seen the power of sport,
not just because of medals.

00:54:37.340 --> 00:54:41.540
Sport brings people together.

00:54:43.260 --> 00:54:48.220
Now it needs to be introduced
into schools.

00:54:48.460 --> 00:54:54.567
Sport has to become a bigger part
of life, not just intellectual work.

00:54:54.817 --> 00:55:01.575
French culture loves film,
but sport is important too.

00:55:02.700 --> 00:55:05.100
So now is a big moment for France,

00:55:05.380 --> 00:55:11.332
because they've realized
that sport matters.

00:55:11.546 --> 00:55:15.410
And now it needs to be integrated
into schools and clubs.

00:55:15.573 --> 00:55:18.776
It's hard right now,
because budgets are being cut,

00:55:18.898 --> 00:55:21.178
including the budget for sport.

00:55:21.613 --> 00:55:28.547
So this is a key moment, and we'll see
how things go in France.

00:55:29.093 --> 00:55:31.653
Nikola, thank you for your time.

00:55:31.989 --> 00:55:37.509
Everyone who knows you says
you've stayed grounded.

00:55:37.680 --> 00:55:39.214
And let's end with your mom.

00:55:39.323 --> 00:55:44.615
She says that more than all the medals
and trophies, what she cherishes most

00:55:44.816 --> 00:55:49.816
is that you and Luka have remained
normal, down-to-earth people.

00:55:50.056 --> 00:55:55.420
And that's no surprise, because people
who are fulfilled and content

00:55:55.646 --> 00:55:59.060
are usually the simplest
and most genuine people.

00:55:59.500 --> 00:56:02.580
All the best, and thank you
for hosting us here in Paris.

00:56:02.820 --> 00:56:07.860
It was truly a pleasure to meet you.
-It was a great honor for me as well.

00:56:08.220 --> 00:56:09.260
Thank you!

